We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accounting and Engineering to:

a) Prioritize and expedite the conduct of a thorough validation and assessment of the dormant CIP balances totaling P84,301,091.98 to determine their current status—whether completed, discontinued, or still ongoing;

b) Jointly establish and implement a formal and documented process flow for the timely monitoring, review, and reclassification of CIP projects;

c) Develop and enforce standardized procedures, clear timelines, and routine reconciliation to ensure accurate and up-to-date reporting of project status;

d) Establish a uniform Project ID system to enable consistent tracking, cross-referencing, and reconciliation of project records between the concerned offices; and

e) Institute internal controls that promote the completeness, neutrality, and accuracy of financial reporting, in compliance with the IPSAS Conceptual Framework, to enhance the relevance, reliability, and fair presentation of the LGU’s financial statements.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor and the officials subject herein to:
1) to submit the required travel authority from the DILG Regional Director for all participants who did the foreign travels in reference to DILG MC No. 2022-147 as the basis for the Regional Director’s duty to act on the LGU’s requests. Submit the same to the Office of the Auditor;
2) Submittheenumeratedlackingdocuments,asdiscussedaboveandshowninAnnexI.1toI.2, otherwise, justify the lack thereof;
3) Submit a justification on the seven (7) days exploration tour at various cities in various states in the USA, which were not part of the mission to be undertaken by the delegates based on the invitation letter and correspondence made to the host organization;
4) Submit a justification on the necessity of all foreign trips, the duration and why it should not be considered irregular, excessive and unnecessary expenditures;
5) Require the concerned officials to communicate with the League of Municipalities of the Philippines – Bukidnon Chapter and the Vice Mayors League of the Philippines and require the same to submit a detailed breakdown of expenses covered by the registration fees paid, including receipts or equivalent documents, to establish the reasonableness, necessity, and allowability of the expenses in accordance with existing government accounting and auditing rules and regulations;
6) Submit an explanation as to why one delegate did not charge, except for the airfare, any expenditures related to the foreign travel;
7) Submit the Certificate of Appearance and/or Participation;
8) Henceforth, ensure that a foreign travel authority is secured from the DILG and that supporting documents are complete in the grant of cash advance and liquidation thereof.

We recommended the management the following, for each of the following conditions:

Non-conduct of physical count of majority of its PPE accounts for CY 2023:

1) Ensure that the preliminary activities prior to inventory taking procedures under COA Circular 2012-002 are followed;
2) Monitor that the Inventory Committee has adequate number of members and representatives from the Accounting and Property Division/Unit for the sole purpose of the one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts of the LGU;
3) Temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee of all their regular duties in order to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until completed;
4) Direct the GSO/Property Unit to record the physical count daily using the ICF per PPE sub-major account group which will be the basis in the preparation of RPCPPE after the physical count;
5) Direct the Inventory Committee/GSO/Property Unit to prepare a List of PPEs Found at Station (Annex B of the Circular) and List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs (Annex C of the Circular) after the physical inventory and submit these lists to the Accounting Unit for recording in the books of accounts of the LGU to establish the existence and proper accountability of the PPE accounts; and
6) Ensure that the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE as provided in COA Circular 2020-006 are strictly observed to facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

Existence of unreconciled balance between General Services Office and the Municipal Accounting Office:

1)Direct the Inventory Committee, Property Unit/GSO and Accounting Unit to reconcile all records and reports pertaining to PPE after the one-time cleansing and establish the correct balances of the PPE account to be recorded in the books of accounts; and
2)Direct the same to review all documents and reports before submission to the Office of the Audit Team to ensure that the details presented thereon are accurate and complete.

Incomplete details of Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE):

1)Direct the Inventory Committee/GSO/Property Unit, in coordination with the Accounting Unit, to use PPELCs/Subsidiary Ledgers (SLs) or, if not available, from Property Cards or other proper records in order to obtain complete details of the items with lacking details as reported under the RPCPPE.

