We recommended to management the following courses of action:
Organize a committee that will be tasked to trace, gather and retrieve the documents of the sixty-six (66) parcels of land (A) to determine with certainty the mode of acquisition, whether through exchange (purchase) or through a non-exchange transaction;
If the land was purchased, determine its acquisition cost based on the gathered appropriate documents, such as the Deed of Sale;
If the land was acquired through non-exchange transaction (ex: donation or grant), the initial cost to be used shall be its fair value as at the date of acquisition.
With the committee’s report as reference, the Municipal Accountant must immediately record the costs of these lands in the books of the LGU, supported with appropriate documents;
Present the Certificate of Titles (COTs) registered in the name of the LGU for the four (4) parcels of land totaling ₱4,450,000.00 (Item B) as concrete confirmations of the LGU’s ownership. For those which have none, process and secure immediately their COTs in favor of the Municipality of Libona. For subsequent acquisitions, ensure that the process of transferring the title in the name of the LGU will be immediately undertaken to avoid the occurrence of the same deficiencies;
Draw up a JEV to adjust the erroneous recording of Land Improvement amounting to P360,000.00 and retrieve all the documents for those properties which were not properly identified in the schedule submitted by the Municipal Accountant and confirm their status with the Municipal Assessor’s records. Take appropriate action based on the status of the properties after retrieval of documents;
Transfer to Brgy Poblacion, if ownership and usage of the property rests with the Barangay, the amount of P350,000.00 which was only part of the total value of lot purchased by the Barangay.
Ensure regular reconciliation of the Municipal Accountant’s ledgers and the Municipal Assessor’s register of lands to assure that all properties owned by the LGU Libona are duly accounted for and to guarantee that they are duly supported with the necessary documents in establishing their control and ownership.
The safekeeping of the Certificate of Titles (COT) and other relevant documents relative to the lands of the municipality shall be assumed by the General Services Division (GSD) which is considered to be the proper office to undertake the responsibility. They must be fully secured and protected and should be filed systematically so that whenever the need for review and verification arises, they can be easily retrieved.

We recommended to management the following courses of action:
Submit the (1) RIS showing issuance of all procured items specified above to the requesting departments, (2) Certified MHO Report of issuance/distribution, duly acknowledge by the recipients, for medicines, medical and laboratory supplies, (3) utilization/ consumption of, vaccines and agricultural supplies, and (4) distribution list and Memorandum of Agreement with beneficiaries for seedlings and cattle;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to verify existence of remaining items on hand pertaining to the above transactions, conduct physical count and submit a report to the Municipal Accountant for appropriate recording in the books;
Instruct the Officer In Charge of the General Services Office to establish a system to properly control and document the receipt and issuance of inventory items to the requesting department;
Strictly impose the submission from concerned offices, the report of issuances and consumption of drugs and medicines, laboratory supplies and other supplies for prompt recording in the books; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to record initially as Inventories, upon payment, all purchases of inventoriable goods. Reversal shall be only upon submission of pertinent documents.

We recommended to management the following courses of action:
Please submit a certification from the Chief Accountant of Bukidnon State University (BukSU) that the instructors and staff paid with honoraria from LGU Libona’s funds were not paid honoraria from BukSU funds for the same particular period;
Strictly abide with the provisions of the Memorandum of Agreement and discontinue the payment of monthly honoraria to full-time and part-time instructors and school personnel of the satellite campus to avoid conflict and to avoid incurrence of any double-payment.

We recommended to management the following courses of action:
Require the Municipal Accountant to comply and submit the lacking documentary requirements, as applicable, with the provisions abovementioned as reference to the auditor for review and verification in order to fully substantiate and to clearly establish the propriety and validity of the transfer and the transaction, in general;
To strictly adhere to the provisions of Section 2.1 of COA Circular 2012-001 when the need to transfer fund to an NGO/PO with a valid cause/purpose arises in the near future.
